<subSubSection pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="88.[151,1436,325,1321]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,793,818]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<quantity box="[327,455,793,817]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.6" metricValueMax="7.1" metricValueMin="6.1" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="mm" value="6.6" valueMax="7.1" valueMin="6.1">6.1–7.1mm</quantity>
long; pronotum, MP yellow, MS dusky yellow, darker than pronotum; frons and labrum sometimes orange; elytral apices rounded (
<figureCitation box="[646,747,829,853]" captionStart="FIGURES 139–146" captionStartId="73.[151,263,1895,1918]" captionTargetBox="[155,1431,199,1859]" captionTargetId="figure-84@73.[151,1436,193,1874]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURES 139–146. Medeopteryx spp. Males (ANIC). 139–142 M. corusca. 143 M. cribellata. 144 M. effulgens. 145 M. fulminea. 146 M. flagrans. 139, 140 abdomen, ventral (139, anterior margin of V4 arrowed) and dorsal; 141 apices of elytra ventral; 142 tergite 8 ventrolateral, flange arrowed; 143–146 terminal abdomen and elytral apices, ventral. These figures share scale lines: 139, 140." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265398" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265398/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 146</figureCitation>
); LOs entire in V7; dimple and hump absent; distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[213,406,865,889]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Medeopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="torricelliensis">
<emphasis box="[213,406,865,889]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">M. torricelliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[422,518,865,889]" captionStart="FIGURES 177–184" captionStartId="80.[151,263,1305,1328]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,187,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-310@80.[151,1436,187,1285]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="FIGURES 177–184. Medeopteryx spp. Males. 177–182 M. similispupillae sp. nov. paratypes. 183 M. torricelliensis. 184 M. sublustris, diagrammatic representation of pronotal sculpturing. 177, 183 dorsal; 178, 179 abdomen, ventral (178) and dorsal; 180–182 aedeagus dorsal (180), left lateral (181) and ventral (182). These figures share scale lines: 180–182" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265414/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 183</figureCitation>
) by its smaller size and the outline of the terminal abdomen; from 
<taxonomicName box="[1272,1400,865,889]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Medeopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hanedai">
<emphasis box="[1272,1400,865,889]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">M. hanedai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the uniformly orange pronotum, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pronotum" baseAuthorityName="Ballantyne" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[603,756,901,925]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Medeopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sublustris">
<emphasis box="[603,756,901,925]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">M. sublustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the smooth surface of the pronotum (see 
<figureCitation box="[1326,1428,901,925]" captionStart="FIGURES 177–184" captionStartId="80.[151,263,1305,1328]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,187,1285]" captionTargetId="figure-310@80.[151,1436,187,1285]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="FIGURES 177–184. Medeopteryx spp. Males. 177–182 M. similispupillae sp. nov. paratypes. 183 M. torricelliensis. 184 M. sublustris, diagrammatic representation of pronotal sculpturing. 177, 183 dorsal; 178, 179 abdomen, ventral (178) and dorsal; 180–182 aedeagus dorsal (180), left lateral (181) and ventral (182). These figures share scale lines: 180–182" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265414/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 184</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A." box="[158,356,937,961]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="117 - 170" refId="ref122195" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (1987 a) Further Revisional Studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 113, 117 - 170." type="journal article" year="1987">Ballantyne 1987a</bibRefCitation>
<figureCitation box="[364,446,937,961]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1950,1973]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-85@39.[151,1436,265,1935]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Australoluciola anthracina type male, Cyclops (MNHN). 9, 10 dorsal (9) and ventral; 11 V6, 7 ventral; 12 pronotum dorsal; 13 type labels; 14 aedeagal sheath ventral; 15-17 aedeagus, dorsal (15), ventral (16) and lateral. These figures share scale lines: 15–17." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265360" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265360/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R." box="[458,771,937,961]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="223 - 305" refId="ref122809" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; McLean, M. R. (1970) Revisional studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae: Luciolini). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 96, 223 - 305." type="journal article" year="1970">Ballantyne &amp; McLean 1970</bibRefCitation>
<figureCitation box="[778,906,937,961]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1950,1973]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-85@39.[151,1436,265,1935]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Australoluciola anthracina type male, Cyclops (MNHN). 9, 10 dorsal (9) and ventral; 11 V6, 7 ventral; 12 pronotum dorsal; 13 type labels; 14 aedeagal sheath ventral; 15-17 aedeagus, dorsal (15), ventral (16) and lateral. These figures share scale lines: 15–17." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265360" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265360/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Figs 14, 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="88.[151,1436,325,1321]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,973,997]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[303,401,973,997]" captionStart="FIGURES 154–159" captionStartId="77.[151,263,1539,1562]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-182@77.[151,1436,193,1518]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 154–159. Medeopteryx spp. female abdomens ventral (not to scale) (ANIC). 154 M. antennata. 155 M. corusca (mating pair Catherine Mission). 156 M. cribellata (G381 mating pair). 157 M. effulgens (Kah New Ireland). 158 M. flagrans (G535). M. fulminea (Kar Kar Island)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5265404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5265404/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 158</figureCitation>
) (Kundiu specimens). 
<quantity box="[663,799,973,997]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.55" metricValueMax="7.2" metricValueMin="5.9" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="mm" value="6.55" valueMax="7.2" valueMin="5.9">5.9–7.2 mm</quantity>
long. Colour: as for male except for dusky brown MS, pale LO in V6, and slightly paler brown V7, 8 which may be irregularly marked laterally in darker brown. Abdomen: posterior margin of V6 not medially emarginate, posterolateral corners rounded; posterior margin of V7 broadly, shallowly and evenly emarginated, posterolateral corners rounded; V8 not indented in median line. Bursa with two sets of wide plates.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="88.[151,1436,325,1321]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1153,1177]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne, L. A." box="[322,587,1153,1177]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="117 - 170" refId="ref122195" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (1987 a) Further Revisional Studies on the firefly genus Pteroptyx Olivier (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 113, 117 - 170." type="journal article" year="1987">Ballantyne (1987a:152)</bibRefCitation>
described the flashing patterns of this species which earned it the common name of &quot;flickerer&quot; used by Lloyd, Buck, Hopkins and others.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="88.[151,1436,325,1321]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
<bibRefCitation author="Lloyd, J. E." box="[199,361,1225,1249]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="991 - 1008" refId="ref127038" refString="Lloyd, J. E. (1973 a) Fireflies of Melanesia: Bioluminescence, Mating Behavior, and Synchronous flashing. Environmental Entomology, 2 (no. 6), 991 - 1008." type="journal article" year="1973">Lloyd (1973a)</bibRefCitation>
described &quot;3 common and distinctive luminescent patterns&quot; and the female behaviour pattern, where &quot;females are attracted to and land near flashing males. In other species (non 
<taxonomicName box="[1131,1239,1262,1285]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1131,1239,1262,1285]" italics="true" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Pteroptyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) studied in New 
<collectingCountry box="[151,232,1297,1321]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Guinea</collectingCountry>
and elsewhere, it is the males that are attracted to stationary luminescing females&quot;.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
